INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'b3f9c5e2-5cc6-4942-a908-3c02d3df35d0',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Databricks SQL Warehouses — OLAP-First Design and Why You Shouldn't Replace Postgres$escape$,
  $escape$Delta Lake stores data as Parquet files — columnar format. Reads scan only requested columns, not full rows, making aggregations across billions of events extremely efficient. Databricks SQL Warehouses run on Photon, a vectorized C++ engine purpose-built for this columnar layout.

This is fundamentally OLAP territory. Delta is not a replacement for Postgres or MySQL. While Delta supports ACID transactions via its transaction log, DELETE and UPDATE are file-rewrite operations — not in-place row mutations. Running thousands of single-row writes per second against a SQL Warehouse creates small-file debt and compaction pressure fast.

Your primary performance lever for analytical queries is OPTIMIZE ... ZORDER BY — it co-locates related data across Parquet files, enabling Databricks' file-level data skipping to eliminate irrelevant files at query time. This replaces traditional B-tree indexes.

SQL Warehouse type matters too: serverless scales to zero for ad-hoc workloads; classic pro/enterprise clusters sustain heavy ETL pipelines. For transactional application backends, keep your row-store database. Let Databricks own the analytical tier.$escape$,
  $escape$-- Optimize Delta table for analytical scans (OLAP pattern)
OPTIMIZE silver.user_events
ZORDER BY (user_id, event_date);

-- Photon-accelerated columnar scan with file-level data skipping
SELECT
  user_id,
  DATE_TRUNC('month', event_date) AS month,
  COUNT(*)                        AS event_count
FROM silver.user_events
WHERE event_date >= '2024-01-01'
GROUP BY 1, 2
ORDER BY 2 DESC;

-- Anti-pattern: high-frequency single-row MERGE = repeated file rewrites
-- Use batch COPY INTO or micro-batch Structured Streaming instead$escape$,
