INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'cc60397b-b8cf-4171-8f2a-a0f517520555',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Databricks ELT with dbt — Stop Transforming Before You Load$escape$,
  $escape$ETL made sense when warehouses were slow and storage was expensive. Databricks inverts both assumptions: Photon-accelerated SQL and cheap Delta Lake object storage mean transforming inside the warehouse is faster and cheaper than pre-processing before landing.

The pattern: land raw data into a Bronze Delta table via Auto Loader (`cloudFiles` format) or `COPY INTO`, then delegate the T to dbt running against a Databricks SQL warehouse via the `dbt-databricks` adapter. Bronze stays immutable — append-only, schema-on-read. dbt handles Silver and Gold as materialized Delta tables.

The `dbt-databricks` adapter defaults to `file_format='delta'` and supports three-level Unity Catalog namespaces (`catalog.schema.model`) natively in `dbt_project.yml`. Incremental models use Delta's `MERGE` under the hood when `incremental_strategy='merge'` is set — no Spark job, no orchestration glue, just SQL pushed to Photon.

This eliminates a whole class of failure: no serialization between pipeline stages, no schema drift between transform and load, and Unity Catalog lineage traces directly from Bronze source to Gold output without manual tagging.$escape$,
  $escape$-- models/silver/user_events.sql
{{
  config(
    materialized='incremental',
    incremental_strategy='merge',
    unique_key='event_id',
    file_format='delta',
    on_schema_change='sync_all_columns'
  )
}}

SELECT
  event_id,
  user_id,
  event_type,
  event_timestamp,
  from_json(raw_payload, 'STRUCT<action STRING, item_id BIGINT>') AS payload
FROM {{ source('bronze', 'raw_events') }}
{% if is_incremental() %}
  WHERE event_timestamp > (SELECT MAX(event_timestamp) FROM {{ this }})
{% endif %}$escape$,
  $escape$sql$escape$,
