INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'c122a18f-41e2-40f8-996c-ae00df62942c',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Databricks Monitoring — Query History, Cost Dashboards, and Slow Query Alerts$escape$,
  $escape$Databricks exposes full query telemetry through `system.query.history`, a Unity Catalog system table populated within minutes of execution. Every SQL warehouse run lands here: duration, bytes scanned, queued time, user, and status. For slow query alerts, create a Databricks SQL Alert against a query filtering `total_duration_ms > 30000` and `status = 'FINISHED'`, schedule it every 15 minutes, and route to Slack or PagerDuty. Avoid alerting on `RUNNING` rows — propagation lag causes false positives on in-flight queries.

For cost dashboards, join `system.query.history` with `system.billing.usage` on `warehouse_id` and `usage_date` to correlate DBU spend per query pattern or user. Pin a Databricks SQL serverless dashboard with a bar chart of daily DBU from `system.billing.usage` grouped by `sku_name` and `workspace_id`. Per-user attribution uses `executed_by` from query history joined to billing on warehouse and date.

For deep query inspection, enable Query Profiles in SQL Admin Console settings — this gives EXPLAIN-level operator trees and spill metrics for any historical statement without re-execution. Combine with `total_task_duration_ms` to identify CPU-bound vs. I/O-bound bottlenecks.$escape$,
  $escape$-- Identify slow queries via Databricks system.query.history (Unity Catalog)
SELECT
  executed_by,
  warehouse_id,
  ROUND(total_duration_ms   / 1000.0, 1) AS duration_sec,
  ROUND(total_task_duration_ms / 1000.0, 1) AS cpu_sec,
  LEFT(statement_text, 120)              AS query_preview
FROM system.query.history
WHERE
  start_time       >= DATEADD(DAY, -7, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP())
  AND status        = 'FINISHED'
  AND total_duration_ms > 30000
ORDER BY total_duration_ms DESC
LIMIT 25;$escape$,
